  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant criminal and financial consequences:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potential fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets\n\n2. Additional Potential Consequences:\n- Asset seizure\n- Probation\n- Restitution payments\n- Permanent criminal record\n\n3. Specific Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal provisions\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 addresses monetary transactions in criminally derived property\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances, amount of money involved, previous criminal history, and whether the laundering was part of other criminal activities.\n\nNote: I'm providing general legal information based on publicly available sources. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, I recommend consulting a qualified attorney.",
